Let me think about what else could cause the wrong chapter to load. Let me re-read the `effectivePrevChapter` logic more carefully:

```typescript
const effectivePrevChapter = (() => {
    if (!isMultiChapter || !chapterMapData) return prevChapter;
    const { chapterOrder } = chapterMapData;
    const firstLoadedSlug = loadedChapters[0]?.slug;
    const firstLoadedIdx = chapterOrder.indexOf(firstLoadedSlug);
    if (firstLoadedIdx <= 0) return prevChapter;
    const prevSlug = chapterOrder[firstLoadedIdx - 1];
    const prevInfo = allChapters?.find((ch) => ch.slug === prevSlug);
    return {
      slug: `${bookBasePath}/${prevSlug}?page=last`,
      title: prevInfo?.title || prevSlug,
    };
  })();
```

So this is finding the first loaded chapter in the order, then getting the chapter that comes before it in the sequence. When the user clicks back, it navigates to that previous chapter with `?page=last` to jump to the end of it.

Now I'm checking the edge cases. If `indexOf` can't find the slug, it returns -1, which satisfies the `<= 0` check and falls back to `prevChapter` from props. Same thing happens if `loadedChapters[0]` is undefined—the slug becomes undefined, `indexOf` returns -1, and we bail out to the fallback. That's the right behavior. The `prevChapter` prop itself is computed earlier in `renderChapterPage` based on whether there's actually a previous chapter in the book.

